{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509813"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.77,0.1,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4079"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37215"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of a lesion on his penis. He has no other symptoms. He is sexually active with both men and women, engaging in oral, vaginal, and anal intercourse. He reports inconsistent condom use but has no previous sexually transmitted infections. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a single well-demarcated, indurated, painless ulcer on the glans penis. Several non-tender enlarged inguinal lymph nodes are palpable bilaterally. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metronidazole orally for seven days","Benzathine benzylpenicillin intramuscular injection","Ceftriaxone intramuscular injection plus oral azithromycin","Valaciclovir orally for seven days","Doxycycline orally for seven days"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of primary syphilis, caused by \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E. The classic chancre of primary syphilis is a single, well-demarcated, painless, indurated ulcer accompanied by regional lymphadenopathy. The history of being a man who has sex with men places him in a high-risk group for syphilis infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzathine benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E given as a single intramuscular injection is the gold standard treatment for early syphilis (primary, secondary, or early latent syphilis of less than two years duration). This treatment is highly effective and remains the recommended first-line therapy worldwide. If there is any uncertainty regarding the diagnosis of syphilis, consultation with a sexual health service is an option prior to treatment - though in this case, the diagnosis appears consistent with syphilis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat trichomoniasis, bacterial vaginosis, and other anaerobic infections. It would not be effective against syphilis and the clinical presentation is not consistent with these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone plus azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the current recommended treatment for gonorrhoea. While co-infection can occur, the clinical presentation here is classic for primary syphilis rather than gonorrhoea, which typically presents with urethral discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used for herpes simplex virus infections. Genital herpes typically presents with multiple painful vesicles or ulcers, unlike the single painless ulcer seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for chlamydial infections and can be used as an alternative treatment for syphilis in patients with penicillin allergy. However, benzathine benzylpenicillin remains superior for treating syphilis when there are no contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary syphilis typically presents as a single, painless, indurated ulcer (chancre) with regional lymphadenopathy.","Single dose intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin is the first-line treatment for early syphilis.","If the diagnosis of syphilis is uncertain, consultation with a sexual health service is recommended."],"references":["Decision making in syphilis. ASHM Health. Available from: https://ashm.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/Decision-makinginsyphilis_V2.2_Nov21-1_202503.pdf","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Australia; The Australian Government Department of Health; 2021. Trichomoniasis; 2021. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/trichomoniasis/","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Australia; The Australian Government Department of Health; 2021. Syphilis; 2021. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Australia; The Australian Government Department of Health; 2021. Gonorrhoea; 2021. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/gonorrhoea/","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Australia; The Australian Government Department of Health; 2021. Genital Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV); 2021. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/genital-herpes-simplex-virus-hsv/.","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Australia; The Australian Government Department of Health; 2021. Chlamydia; 2021. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T19:02:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T19:03:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4079"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99999"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","